Hidden Regime Inference in U.S. Equities with Out-of-Sample Validation via a Long-Only Allocation Rule

A three state Gaussian Hidden Markov Model is trained on daily log returns of SPY and the leading principal component extracted from two large feature spaces. The model assigns each day to a latent market regime. The strategy holds a long position in SPY when the inferred regime corresponds to the highest expected return state and otherwise allocates to T bill carry with dividend effects removed. Signals are generated at time T and executed at the market open on T+1 with transaction costs applied.

06 - About

Model Architecture

This model pipeline uses a fairly vanilla HMM with only some slightly fancy ensembling and a voting machine to smooth transitions as a second-step in the pipeline.

Where is the alpha then?

Features are the foundation of alphas, no level of modeling complexity or advanced architecture can transform redundant features into meaningful alphas.

Feature Engineering

The model was trained on two distinct feature sets which will go undisclosed. By virtue, I advocate for large feature spaces with high compression. While it's possible to engineer a single, statistically significant feature, combining multiple features into an ensemble that consolidates them into one dimension tends to outperform the former approach.

The features do still need to be good alphas. It's important to note that while your inputs don't need to be the best, they should still be valuable in the first place. Achieving this takes some effort, the bar is lower per feature but you need more of them.

Feature Hints

Empirically, I have found that statistical strength often dominates raw signal magnitude. Rather than feeding engineered features directly into the model, I transform them through two tailed t-test and use the resulting test statistics as inputs. In effect, this standardises each feature into a signal to noise measure, which improves comparability across heterogeneous feature spaces.

Applying PCA to these standardised statistics tends to produce more coherent latent factors than applying PCA to the raw features themselves. The principal components then represent common structure in statistical significance rather than common structure in levels.

Within equity markets, feature families that have exhibited persistent explanatory power include:

  • Implied volatility surface metrics, particularly skew and term structure dispersion
  • Realised volatility measures across multiple lookbacks
  • Futures roll yield and carry based signals
  • State space estimates such as Kalman filtered trend slopes
  • Volume return interaction measures, including lagged correlations
  • Time series momentum and signal processing indicators
  • Index constituent correlation structure and dispersion
  • Dealer gamma exposure
  • Macroeconomic data

Overfitting Concerns

Large feature spaces will only overfit if you leave them large, but they are actually less likely to overfit if you compress them compared to hand-selecting features where you have likely been data mining through the past. High compression makes no assumptions of features so long as they are appropriately selected and segregated.

Robust Dimension Reduction

Principal component analysis (PCA) involves decomposing a data matrix into a set of orthogonal principal components that capture the maximum variance in the data. The PCA problem is typically framed as finding a low-rank approximation of the data matrix. This is achieved through singular value decomposition of the covariance matrix or directly using matrix factorisation.

When features are correlated, the covariance matrix will have off-diagonal elements that are non-zero. This means that there are linear dependencies between the variables, and PCA will be able to find new axes that capture this structure.

Or to frame it geometrically: If the original variables are correlated, the data points tend to cluster along certain directions in the multidimensional space. PCA will find these directions by identifying the eigenvectors corresponding to the largest eigenvalues. The new dimensions will capture the main trends or directions in the data, leading to effective dimension reduction.

When the variables are uncorrelated, the covariance matrix is diagonal, meaning that the off-diagonal covariances are zero. In this case, each variable has no linear relationship with the others. Since the covariance matrix is diagonal, the eigenvectors are simply the standard basis vectors, and the eigenvalues represent the variances of each original variable. When applying PCA on uncorrelated features, you are essentially just sorting the original features by their variance, and no dimensionality reduction occurs unless we decide to discard variables with low variance. This is because the new axes align with the original features.

In other words, PCA does not reduce the dimensionality in any meaningful way when the variables are uncorrelated, it merely orders the variables by variance without changing the structure of the data.

Robust PCA (RPCA) is an extension for a range of applications, particularly those in financial engineering where outliers and corrupt data will skew your distribution. RPCA tackles a pesky limitation where PCA is sensitive to outliers. RPCA introduces a mechanism to handle outliers effectively. The key idea is to decompose the data matrix into two components: a low-rank matrix L representing the true underlying structure and a sparse matrix S capturing the outliers or anomalies. The goal is to minimise the impact of the outliers while preserving the true data structure. This pipeline applies traditional PCA to the low-rank component of an RPCA.
